<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-04-23T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-04-23T14:00:00-05:00" n="523" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d523">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1111 <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker, Charles</persName>/80:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Consul General at Shanghai (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_CES1" type="to">Cunningham</persName>)</hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-04-23T14:00:00-05:00">April 23, 1932—2
                                p.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>151. For the Minister. Your April 23, noon. The Department is gratified
                            at the energetic presentation made by you of the <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Baker</persName> case to Chinese
                            authorities at Nanking.</p>
                        <p>Referring to paragraph 8 of your telegram under reference Department
                            grants you authorization requested to delay assigning special officer to
                            watch this case.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_CWR1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Castle</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>